---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
---
<BaseLayout title="BridgeAIChat Beta" description="Run one chat interface for AI CLIs across your own devices.">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="surface">
      <div class="eyebrow">Developer Control Plane</div>
      <h1>Operate the AI tools on your machines from one clean chat surface.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        BridgeAIChat gives you a shared chat UI for Codex, Claude, and other CLI-native tools running on your laptop,
        desktop, VPS, or Raspberry Pi. The gateway stays on your side, the agents stay on your devices, and Tailscale
        ties the whole thing together.
      </p>
      <div class="pill-row">
        <span class="pill">Codex-first beta path</span>
        <span class="pill">Homebrew install direction</span>
        <span class="pill">Self-hosted control plane</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="button primary" href="/downloads">Install the beta</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/docs/quickstart">Read the quickstart</a>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-grid">
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>1 UI</strong>
          <span>for your laptop, VPS, and edge boxes</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>0 hosted runtime</strong>
          <span>required for the first beta</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>brew install</strong>
          <span>target path for public community setup</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
        <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
        <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
      </div>
      <pre>brew install bridge-ai-chat/tap/bridge-app
brew install bridge-ai-chat/tap/bridge-agent

bridge-gateway

# on another device
bash "$(brew --prefix)/share/bridge-agent/install-agent.sh"

gateway
  → web UI
  → tailscale
  → bridge-agent
  → codex / claude / local CLI</pre>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-gap grid three">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="eyebrow">Own the Runtime</div>
      <h2>Keep execution where your tools already live.</h2>
      <p>BridgeAIChat does not replace your local CLI tools. It wraps them with a better control surface and a device-aware transport layer.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="eyebrow">Fleet Visibility</div>
      <h2>See which machine answered.</h2>
      <p>Each device registers into the gateway independently, so follow-ups stay grounded in the right runtime and working directory.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="eyebrow">Community Beta</div>
      <h2>Built for technical testers first.</h2>
      <p>The first public release is optimized for power users, homelab builders, and engineers who want fast local control before enterprise layers arrive.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-gap grid two">
    <div class="card stack">
      <div class="eyebrow">How It Works</div>
      <h2>Minimal architecture, clear boundaries.</h2>
      <div class="note"><strong>bridge-app</strong> runs the gateway and serves the UI.</div>
      <div class="note"><strong>bridge-agent</strong> runs on each remote machine and bridges to local AI CLIs through tmux-backed execution.</div>
      <div class="note"><strong>bridge-docs</strong> is the public site, install guide, and release map.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="card stack">
      <div class="eyebrow">Best Fit</div>
      <h2>Who the beta is for.</h2>
      <ul class="list tight">
        <li>Developers using Codex or Claude CLI on more than one machine</li>
        <li>Homelab operators with GPU boxes, VPS hosts, or Raspberry Pi nodes</li>
        <li>Platform engineers who want a private, inspectable AI runtime path</li>
        <li>Early community testers who prefer self-hosted infrastructure over SaaS orchestration</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
